04337nam a22006255i 9780300150179DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20072007ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a73089820  a(OCoLC)1029831006  a97803001501797 a10.12987/97803001501792doi  a(DE-B1597)486632  a(OCoLC)1024003963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT00aBV4847b.W46 1973 4aJK325b.P87 2007 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a320.473/0492221 aKaestle, Carl F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOriginalism, Federalism, and the American Constitutional Enterprise :bA Historical Inquiry /cLawrence C. Stedman, Carl F. Kaestle, Helen Damon-Moore. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction. The Inquiry -- t1. American Constitutional Federalism as a Normative Problem -- tPart I. Structural Intrinsics -- t2. Federalism as Doubly Blurred -- t3. Federalism as Fractionated -- t4. Federalism as Instrumental -- t5. Federalism as Contingent -- tPart II. Consequential Dynamics -- t6. Kaleidoscopic Politics -- t7. Readjusting Components -- t8. Contested Authorities -- t9. Evolving Understandings -- tPart III. Conclusion -- t10. The “Arduous Enterprise” -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this lively historical examination of American federalism, a leading scholar in the field refutes the widely accepted notion that the founding fathers carefully crafted a constitutional balance of power between the states and the federal government. Edward A. Purcell Jr. bases his argument on close analysis of the Constitution’s original structure and the ways that structure both induced and accommodated changes over the centuries. There was no clear agreement among the founding fathers regarding the “true” nature of American federalism, Purcell contends, nor was there a consensus on “correct” lines dividing state and national authority. Furthermore, even had there been some true “original” understanding, the elastic and dynamic nature of the constitutional structure would have made it impossible for subsequent generations to maintain any “original” or permanent balance. The author traces the evolution of federalism through the centuries, focusing particularly on shifting interpretations founded on political interests. He concludes with insights into current issues of federal power and a discussion of the grounds on which legitimate decisions about federal and state power should rest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aFederal governmentzUnited States. 0aMothersvPrayers and devotions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aDamon-Moore, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStedman, Lawrence C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012203940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015017940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300150179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300150179/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY